Despite this, USPSTF's guidance still directly impacts access to essential care.

This is why I, along with @RepBonnie @repMMM & @RepAnnWagner, have called on USPSTF to improve access to lifesaving, innovative colorectal screening tests through an expedited review process.

@CDCgov The problem? USPSTF has not updated its colorectal cancer screening guidelines since 2021.

Now, there is more to this story. A June 5th circuit ruling challenged USPSTF's structure and ACA coverage mandate, pausing its application in LA, MS, and my home state of TX - for now.

@CDCgov The U.S. Preventive Services Task Force (USPSTF) plays a central role here:

USPSTF-recommended treatments & screenings must be covered by private insurance. This is essential to ensure more Americans can access life-saving preventative care without financial barriers.

@CDCgov The good news? Newer, less invasive screening tests have been developed in recent years, thanks to impressive advancements in this space.

In fact, these tests are intended to specifically increase colorectal screening rates in Americans aged 45 - 49.

50,000 Americans die from colorectal cancer a year. According to @CDCgov 68% of deaths are preventable through screenings.  

Yet - 10s of millions of at-risk Americans, especially men of color, face access barriers or simply find colonoscopies to be too uncomfortable. I get it.

Colorectal cancer is one of the deadliest for men under 50, but it’s also one of the most preventable. If you find colonoscopies uncomfortable, you’re not alone. Luckily, newer tests are offering a better way.

The problem? USPSTF must update their screening guidelines.
